SIMPLE: bye
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Bye
<hw>Bye</hw> <pr>(b⟦imac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A thing
not directly aimed at; something which is a secondary object of regard;
an object by the way, etc.; as in <xex>on</xex> or <xex>upon the
bye</xex>, <it>i. e.</it>, in passing; indirectly; by implication.</def>
<mark>[Obs. except in the phrase <it>by the bye</it>.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Synod of Dort condemneth upon the <qex>bye</qex> even the
discipline of the Church of England.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>A run made upon a missed ball;
<as>as, to steal a <ex>bye</ex></as>.</def> <rj><au>T.
Hughes.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In various sports in which the contestants are drawn
in pairs, the position or turn of one left with no opponent in
consequence of an odd number being engaged; <as>as, to draw a
<ex>bye</ex> in a round of a tennis tournament</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Golf)</fld> <def>The hole or holes of a stipulated
course remaining unplayed at the end of a match.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>By the bye</b></col>, <cd>in passing; by way of
digression; apropos to the matter in hand.</cd> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>by the by</asp>.]</altsp></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Bye</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Bye
<hw>Bye</hw> <pr>(b⟦imac⟧)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>b⟦ymac⟧</ets>; cf. Icel. <ets>byg⟦edh⟧</ets> dwelling,
<ets>byggja</ets>, <ets>b⟦umac⟧a</ets>, to dwell ⟦root⟧97.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A dwelling.</def> <rj><au>Gibson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In certain games, a station or place of an
individual player.</def> <rj><au>Emerson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>By-election</ent>⟦br⟧
